60|$|Speaking of negroes, {{recalls the}} looks of {{interest}} with which negro- sailors are regarded when they walk the Liverpool streets. In Liverpool indeed the negro steps with a prouder pace, and lifts {{his head like a}} man; for here, no such exaggerated feeling exists in respect to him, as in America. Three or four times, I encountered our black steward, dressed very handsomely, and walking arm in arm with a good-looking English woman. In New York, such a couple would have been mobbed in three minutes; and the steward would have been lucky to escape with whole limbs. Owing to the friendly reception extended to them, and the unwonted immunities they enjoy in Liverpool, the <b>black</b> <b>cooks</b> and stewards of American ships are very much attached to the place and like to make voyages to it.|$|R
